description:
Started being published quarterly then became published monthly

Although Super Heroes were still DC's bread and butter, the company made a preliminary entry into the funny animal market with the launch of Funny Stuff. Edited by Sheldon Mayer, the anthology title showcased a number of new animal humor features including; Rufus Lion, Blackie Bear, Bulldog Drumhead and McSnurtle the Turtle who could change into a super hero called the Terrific Whatsit.

Series continued as Dodo and The Frog.

deck:
Spin off from Scribbly appearances in Popular Comics.
Started in Aug 1948
description: Scribbly JIbbet, the boy cartoonist written and drawn by Sheldon Mayer, received his own title in 1948 after years of appearances in All-American Comics and Comic Cavalcade. Scribbly was the beneficiary of a teen comics boom that also saw the launch of "Leave it to Binky." The series still contained Mayer's work but now focused more on romance and Scribbly's attempts to get a steady job, with the previously regular guest star (Red Tornado) notably absent from its pages. During the 15 issue run of Scribbly, the character also appeared in "Leave it to Binky" and "Buzzy."
name: Scribbly

deck: Benny Hill had a comic book? Sort of
description:
Coming out at the end of the year the Radio Fun Annual was made up of reprints from the comic weekly Radio Fun, which in turn consisted of short comic strips based on well known British radio personalities of the time, as well as the occasional adventure strip such as The Falcon. 

The annuals ran between 96 and 110 pages with thick cardboard covers.  

Running from 1939 to 1961 the last featured main character was Benny Hill.

Who are the Secret Avengers? A new era begins as Marvel's hottest team takes a 21st century twist! description:
Herschel – Father Herschel to those who knew him years ago, just plain Herschel to those he meets now – is a man of waning faith. Somewhere ahead of Herschel, forging the Devil’s Trail across the old west, is Jericho – an eyeless man with a serpentine smile. Jericho’s words can make even the smartest man’s head spin. His touch is the touch of death itself.

Herschel senses this. Somehow, he knows it. He fears it. And he needs to face it. But facing Jericho means traveling the Devil’s Trail – no place for a man of waning faith. Unless, of course, that man is handy with the iron…
name: The Devil's Trail
